Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the rigatoni. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) with a #garlic press{}.

Trim and discard the root and dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}(trimmed, root and dark green leafy part discarded). Halve lengthways, then thinly slice.

When your pan of water is boiling, add the @rigatoni pasta{180%g} and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, melt the @butter{20%g} with a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the leek and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-6%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Pour in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{125%ml}. Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until slightly reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest and cut the @lemon{1}(zested and cut into wedges). Pick the @tarragon{1}(leaves picked and finely chopped, stalks discarded). In a small #bowl{}, combine the lemon zest and half the tarragon. Set your gremolata aside.

Once the water in the frying pan has reduced, stir through the @creme fraiche{150%g} and @peas{120%g}. Simmer until thickened and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add the cooked pasta and toss to combine, then remove from the heat. Stir through the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and remaining tarragon. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and a good squeeze of lemon juice. Add a splash more water if needed.

Share the pasta primavera between your #bowls{}. Sprinkle over the tarragon gremolata to finish. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!